**Pre-Design Classification:** `contradictory_requirements`

Requirements 2 (strong consistency — no double-assignment) and 3 (high availability during DB node failure) are in direct tension per the CAP theorem. However, I can still provide substantial architectural analysis with options. Let me reason through this fully.

```json
{
  "executive_summary": "The courier assignment system has a fundamental CAP theorem tension: requirement 2 (strong consistency — no double-assignment) and requirement 3 (high availability during DB node failure) cannot both be fully satisfied during a network partition or failover window. The team must decide which requirement to relax at the margin. I present two viable architectures — one consistency-favoring, one availability-favoring — and recommend the consistency-favoring approach given that double-assignment has direct business cost (two couriers dispatched for one order). The 200ms latency and 2-engineer team constraints are achievable with either approach.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Assignment Service",
        "responsibility": "Receives order-placed events, selects optimal available courier, and atomically claims the assignment. Stateless horizontally-scaled service.",
        "boundaries": "Owns assignment logic only. Does not own courier profiles or order lifecycle. Communicates via events and synchronous DB calls."
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Availability Store",
        "responsibility": "Single source of truth for courier availability state. Must enforce the invariant that a courier can only be assigned to one active order at a time.",
        "boundaries": "Owns courier availability and active-assignment state. Does NOT own courier profile data (name, vehicle, rating)."
      },
      {
        "name": "Order Intake Gateway",
        "responsibility": "Receives incoming orders, validates, and emits order-placed events to trigger assignment.",
        "boundaries": "Owns order creation. Hands off to Assignment Service immediately."
      },
      {
        "name": "Assignment Event Log",
        "responsibility": "Records all assignment decisions (assigned, released, failed) for audit, debugging, and downstream consumers.",
        "boundaries": "Append-only. Downstream systems (notifications, tracking) consume from here."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Intake Gateway",
        "to": "Assignment Service",
        "contract": "Synchronous RPC or async event (order_id, pickup_location, delivery_location, priority). Must complete handoff in <50ms to leave budget for assignment.",
        "coupling_type": "event (preferred) or thin RPC"
      },
      {
        "from": "Assignment Service",
        "to": "Courier Availability Store",
        "contract": "Atomic claim operation: claim_courier(courier_id, order_id) → success/conflict. Uses SELECT FOR UPDATE or compare-and-swap. Must complete in <100ms.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous — unavoidable for consistency guarantee"
      },
      {
        "from": "Assignment Service",
        "to": "Assignment Event Log",
        "contract": "Async emit of assignment_completed or assignment_failed events. Fire-and-forget with at-least-once delivery.",
        "coupling_type": "async event"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. Order placed → Gateway validates → emits order.placed event (or sync call). 2. Assignment Service receives event, queries Courier Availability Store for nearby available couriers (read). 3. Selects best candidate, issues atomic claim_courier(courier_id, order_id) (write with row-level lock). 4. On success: emits assignment.completed event. On conflict (courier already claimed): retries with next candidate. 5. Total budget: <50ms routing + <50ms candidate query + <100ms atomic claim + retry margin = <200ms.",
    "patterns_used": []
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Courier Assignment",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": [
          "CourierAvailability (aggregate root — enforces single-assignment invariant, tracks courier status: available/assigned/offline)",
          "AssignmentRequest (entity — represents an in-flight assignment attempt with order_id, candidate list, outcome)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          "Order (aggregate root — lifecycle from placed to delivered, but assignment logic is NOT here)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Courier Profile",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          "CourierProfile (aggregate root — name, vehicle type, rating, location — read by Assignment but owned separately)"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Courier Assignment",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order Management publishes order.placed events; Assignment consumes them. Order Management does not depend on Assignment internals."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Courier Profile",
        "downstream": "Courier Assignment",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Assignment reads courier location/status from Profile context's read model. Assignment conforms to Profile's schema."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Option A (RECOMMENDED): Favor consistency — use PostgreSQL with synchronous standby and automatic failover (e.g., Patroni/pg_auto_failover). Accept a brief unavailability window (5-30s) during failover.",
      "gains": "Zero risk of double-assignment. Simple mental model. Row-level locking via SELECT FOR UPDATE is battle-tested. 2 engineers can operate this confidently.",
      "sacrifices": "During DB failover (5-30 seconds), assignment requests will fail or queue. Some orders will experience >200ms latency during failover. Requires the product team to accept this window.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Redis with Redlock — faster but Redlock has known safety issues (Martin Kleppmann's analysis); not suitable when double-assignment has real business cost",
        "DynamoDB with conditional writes — strong consistency mode available but adds AWS coupling and operational complexity for a 2-person team"
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Option B: Favor availability — use an in-memory lock (Redis) with async DB persistence. Accept rare double-assignment risk during Redis failover, mitigate with reconciliation.",
      "gains": "Sub-10ms lock acquisition. System stays available during DB node failure. Extremely fast.",
      "sacrifices": "Redis failover can cause split-brain → two services may assign the same courier. Requires a reconciliation process to detect and fix double-assignments. More operational complexity for a 2-person team.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "CockroachDB — strong consistency + multi-node availability, but significant operational overhead for 2 engineers",
        "Application-level optimistic locking with retry — simpler but higher contention under load"
      ]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Courier selection algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "Start with nearest-available courier (simple distance query). Evolve to scoring model (distance + rating + current load) without changing the assignment contract. The selection logic is isolated inside Assignment Service."
    },
    {
      "area": "Assignment event consumers",
      "evolution_path": "New downstream systems (analytics, courier notifications, ETA calculation) can subscribe to assignment events without modifying the core assignment path."
    },
    {
      "area": "Database technology",
      "evolution_path": "The atomic claim operation is behind a repository interface. Could migrate from PostgreSQL to another store if scale demands it, without changing service logic."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Single-assignment invariant enforcement",
      "reason": "This MUST be enforced at the database level (row-level lock or unique constraint), not in application code. Distributed application-level locks are unreliable. This is intentional rigidity — the correctness guarantee is non-negotiable."
    },
    {
      "area": "Synchronous write path for claiming a courier",
      "reason": "The claim operation cannot be made eventually consistent — it must be synchronous and atomic. This limits the system's theoretical availability ceiling, but it's the correct trade-off for the domain."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "CAP tension: during a DB failover window (5-30s), assignment requests will fail, violating the availability requirement",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Product team must decide: accept brief unavailability (Option A) or accept rare double-assignment (Option B). There is no third option per CAP theorem. Recommendation: Option A with a client-side retry queue that buffers requests during failover."
    },
    {
      "risk": "200ms latency budget is tight when including network hops, DB query, and atomic write",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Pre-compute courier availability in a materialized view or cache. Use spatial indexing (PostGIS) for location queries. Keep Assignment Service co-located with DB to minimize network latency. Budget: 50ms candidate query + 50ms atomic claim + 50ms overhead = 150ms with 50ms margin."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Hot courier contention — popular couriers get multiple concurrent claim attempts",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Assignment Service should select top-N candidates and attempt claims in order. Row-level locking means only one request blocks; others fail fast and move to next candidate. Average case is 1-2 attempts."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Operational burden on 2-person team for running HA PostgreSQL",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Use a managed database service (AWS RDS Multi-AZ, GCP Cloud SQL HA, or equivalent). Automatic failover is handled by the provider. This is the single most impactful ops simplification."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "[PROVISIONAL — pending product decision on consistency vs availability trade-off] Recommend Option A: PostgreSQL with synchronous replication and managed automatic failover. Use SELECT FOR UPDATE with SKIP LOCKED for atomic courier claiming. Deploy Assignment Service as a stateless container with 2-3 replicas. Use PostGIS for spatial queries to find nearby couriers. Accept 5-30s unavailability during rare DB failover events. This is the simplest architecture a 2-person team can operate confidently while protecting the business-critical no-double-assignment invariant.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/assignment/service.ts — Assignment Service: receives order events, selects candidates, claims courier",
      "src/assignment/repository.ts — CourierAvailabilityRepository: atomic claim_courier operation with SELECT FOR UPDATE",
      "src/assignment/candidate-selector.ts — Courier ranking/selection logic (isolated for easy evolution)",
      "migrations/001_courier_availability.sql — Table with courier_id (PK), status (available/assigned), current_order_id, location (PostGIS geometry), updated_at",
      "migrations/002_assignment_log.sql — Append-only assignment event log for audit"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Repository pattern for DB access. Domain events for downstream communication. Retry-with-next-candidate for contention handling. Feature flags for algorithm changes.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT implement distributed locking in application code (e.g., Redlock) for the primary consistency guarantee — use database-level locking",
      "DO NOT make the claim operation async or eventually consistent — the double-assignment invariant requires synchronous atomic writes",
      "DO NOT put courier selection logic inside the database query — keep it in application code for testability and evolvability",
      "DO NOT use a single DB instance without replication — this makes requirement 3 impossible",
      "DO NOT over-engineer for scale prematurely — a single PostgreSQL instance handles tens of thousands of assignments per second with row-level locking"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [
    {
      "type": "contradictory_requirements",
      "description": "Requirements 2 (strong consistency — no double-assignment) and 3 (high availability during DB node failure) are in fundamental tension per the CAP theorem. During a database failover event, the system must choose: reject requests (preserving consistency) or accept requests with risk of double-assignment (preserving availability). Both cannot be fully guaranteed simultaneously during a failure.",
      "routed_to": "Bird",
      "options": [
        "Option A: Favor consistency — accept 5-30s unavailability during DB failover. Orders queue and retry. Zero double-assignment risk.",
        "Option B: Favor availability — use Redis-based locking with async DB sync. System stays up during DB failure but rare double-assignments possible. Requires reconciliation process.",
        "Option C: Tiered approach — use strong consistency for high-value orders, optimistic assignment for low-value orders. Adds complexity but lets the team tune the trade-off per order type."
      ],
      "recommendation": "Option A. Double-assignment has direct business cost (two couriers dispatched, customer confusion, refund liability). A 5-30s failover window is rare and recoverable. A 2-person team cannot safely operate the reconciliation system that Option B requires."
    }
  ],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 55,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "The CAP tension between requirements 2 and 3 is real and must be explicitly resolved by the product team",
      "PostgreSQL with SELECT FOR UPDATE is the right consistency mechanism for a 2-person team",
      "The 200ms latency budget is achievable with co-located services and spatial indexing",
      "Domain model boundaries (Assignment as core context, Order and Profile as supporting) are clean"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Which side of the CAP trade-off the product team will accept — this changes the architecture materially",
      "Expected order volume and courier count — affects whether single-node PostgreSQL suffices or sharding is needed",
      "Geographic distribution of the service — single-region vs multi-region changes the replication and latency story entirely"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Single-region deployment (multi-region would make the CAP tension significantly worse)",
      "Order volume fits within a single PostgreSQL instance's capacity (tens of thousands per second)",
      "The team is willing to use a managed database service rather than self-hosting",
      "200ms is measured from order-placed event received to assignment-confirmed, not including upstream network latency"
    ]
  }
}
```

